        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: make repair tests portable on Windows",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nClawSweeper's repair validation path and several test fixtures assumed POSIX command lookup, LF-only source reads, executable fake `gh` shims, and `/`-only path containment. That made Windows local validation fail even when the runtime behavior being tested was otherwise portable.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThis updates repair command execution and GitHub CLI helpers to support explicit tool shims on Windows, makes `.cmd`/`.bat` validation commands run through `cmd.exe`, fixes state-root publish containment with platform-native path checks, and normalizes source-fixture reads where assertions inspect tracked files. The test fixtures now use explicit Node-backed fake tools instead of depending on extensionless executables being discoverable through `PATH`.\n\n## User Impact\n\nMaintainers can run the ClawSweeper repair and unit suites from Windows without patching local tool shims or line endings. The state publish path also no longer rejects valid state-root paths on Windows.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- `pnpm install --frozen-lockfile` passed.\n- `pnpm run test:repair` passed: 569 tests, 569 pass.\n- `pnpm run test:unit` passed: 547 tests, 546 pass, 1 skipped.\n- `pnpm run build:all` passed.\n- `pnpm run lint` passed.\n- `pnpm run format:check` passed.\n- `pnpm run check` passed, including `check:active-surface`, `check:limits`, `build:all`, `lint`, `test:unit`, `test:repair`, changed/full coverage, and `format:check`.\n- `codex review -c service_tier='fast' --uncommitted` passed with no actionable correctness issues; the review also ran focused build/unit/repair checks.",
